# Therum Technologies — Cursor Rules
# Stack: Next.js · Supabase · Xero API · Stripe Connect · Vercel
# Last updated: April 2026

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 1. PROJECT CONTEXT
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

You are building Therum — a B2B SaaS platform for UK talent representation
and influencer marketing agencies. It automates financial operations:
deal pipeline management, milestone invoicing (the INV/SBI/COM triplet),
talent payouts, VAT threshold monitoring, and Xero reconciliation.

Three portals: Agency, Finance, and Talent.
Two invoicing models set at agency level: SELF_BILLING and ON_BEHALF.

This is financial software. Mistakes have real monetary consequences.
Always prioritise correctness and auditability over cleverness or brevity.


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 2. MULTI-TENANCY & ROW LEVEL SECURITY (CRITICAL)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

Therum is multi-tenant. Each agency is a completely isolated tenant.
Agencies must NEVER be able to see, access, or modify another agency's data.

ALWAYS:
- Every Supabase table that holds agency data MUST have an `agency_id` column
- Every RLS policy MUST filter by `agency_id = auth.uid()` or via a
  `get_current_agency_id()` helper function
- When creating any new table, write the RLS policy in the same migration file
- When querying Supabase from server-side code, always include agency_id in
  the WHERE clause as a second layer of protection

NEVER:
- Query Supabase without RLS enabled on the table
- Use the Supabase service role key on the client side — ever
- Disable RLS on any table containing agency, deal, invoice, talent,
  milestone, or payout data
- Trust client-supplied agency_id values — always derive from the
  authenticated session server-side

Example correct RLS policy:
  CREATE POLICY "agency_isolation" ON deals
    FOR ALL USING (agency_id = get_current_agency_id());


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 3. ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES & SECRETS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

NEVER:
- Use SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY anywhere in /app, /components, or
  client-side code. It belongs only in /app/api route handlers.
- Hardcode any API key, secret, or credential in source code
- Use NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix for any secret — NEXT_PUBLIC_ values are
  visible to every user in their browser

ALWAYS:
- Access secrets via process.env.VARIABLE_NAME in API routes only
- Validate that required env vars exist at startup, not at call time
- Keep a .env.example file updated with all required variable names
  (but never their values)

Required environment variables for Therum:
  SUPABASE_URL
  SUPABASE_ANON_KEY
  SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY        (server only — never NEXT_PUBLIC_)
  XERO_CLIENT_ID
  XERO_CLIENT_SECRET
  XERO_WEBHOOK_KEY                 (for HMAC validation)
  STRIPE_SECRET_KEY                (server only — never NEXT_PUBLIC_)
  STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET            (for webhook validation)
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL         (safe — public URL only)
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY    (safe — anon key only)


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 4. FINANCIAL LOGIC RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

These rules reflect how UK talent agency finance actually works.
Getting them wrong causes real accounting errors.

INVOICE TRIPLET (SELF_BILLING model):
  INV  = Client Invoice     Agency → Brand client      ACCREC in Xero
  SBI  = Self-Billing       Agency → Talent (on their  ACCPAY in Xero
         Invoice             behalf) · Gross deal value
  COM  = Commission         Agency → Talent            ACCREC in Xero
         Invoice             Commission amount only

INVOICE TRIPLET (ON_BEHALF model):
  OBI  = On-Behalf Invoice  Agency → Brand client (billing as agent  ACCREC in Xero
                             on behalf of talent, not in own name)
  CN   = Credit Note        Same client contact as OBI; mirrors OBI gross on the
                             CN account line — pairs with OBI so gross does not
                             sit as agency revenue on P&L (see GEMINI.md)
  COM  = Commission         Agency → Client · Commission amount only  ACCREC in Xero

HOW THE ON_BEHALF FLOW WORKS — step by step:

  1. Milestone marked complete by Agency portal
  2. Triplet generated: OBI + CN + COM document numbers (CN mirrors OBI gross)
  3. Finance Portal approval: OBI, settlement CN, and COM are pushed to Xero
     in the same batch (same Xero session). CN amount = OBI gross exactly.
  4. Brand client pays OBI
  5. Xero webhook fires — OBI marked PAID in Therum; milestone can become
     payout-eligible (CN already exists in Xero from step 3)
  6. Net payout to talent = OBI gross − COM amount
     Example: £10,000 OBI − £2,000 COM = £8,000 net to talent
  7. Payout run initiated in Finance Portal — talent receives net amount

KEY ACCOUNTING DISTINCTION between SELF_BILLING and ON_BEHALF:

  SELF_BILLING:
    Agency revenue line = COM only (commission income)
    SBI sits as COGS (cost of sale) on agency P&L
    INV gross revenue nets against SBI to leave COM as net income

  ON_BEHALF:
    Agency revenue line = COM only (commission income)
    OBI is NOT agency revenue — agency is acting as billing agent
    CN cancels OBI so it never sits as agency income on P&L
    Only COM flows through as agency income
    Net accounting effect on agency P&L is identical to SELF_BILLING

InvoiceTriplet schema — ON_BEHALF model fields:
  obiNumber           — populated for ON_BEHALF, null for SELF_BILLING
  cnNumber            — populated for ON_BEHALF, null for SELF_BILLING
  invNumber           — populated for SELF_BILLING, null for ON_BEHALF
  sbiNumber           — populated for SELF_BILLING, null for ON_BEHALF
  comNumber           — populated for BOTH models always
  invoicingModel      — snapshot of model at generation time (immutable)

ALWAYS:
- Check `agency.invoicingModel` before generating any invoice set
- Generate all three linked documents atomically — never partially
- Store `invoicingModel` as a snapshot on InvoiceTriplet at generation time
  so historical records are correct even if the agency changes model later
- For ON_BEHALF: push OBI, settlement CN (full OBI gross), and COM together on
  Finance approval so P&L netting is correct; store `xeroCnId` on the triplet
- Track payout status at MILESTONE level, never at deal level
  A deal with 3 milestones has 3 independent payout states
- Net payout calculation is the same for both models:
  Net payout = Gross deal value − Commission amount
  SELF_BILLING example: £12,000 SBI − £2,400 COM = £9,600 to talent
  ON_BEHALF example:    £12,000 OBI − £2,400 COM = £9,600 to talent
- For ON_BEHALF: payout eligibility requires OBI confirmed PAID in Xero via
  webhook; settlement CN must already exist from the approval push (`xeroCnId`)

DATES — these are three distinct concepts, never conflate them:
  invoiceDate    = Tax point (HMRC). Editable by Finance pre-push.
                   This is what determines VAT period.
  deliveryDueDate = When the content/deliverable is due
  issuedAt       = Approval audit timestamp on InvoiceTriplet. Set on PENDING
                   creation (placeholder), overwritten atomically with
                   approvalStatus='APPROVED' inside complete_xero_push RPC,
                   then immutable (enforced by DB trigger).

TALENT PORTAL — model-specific visibility rules:
  SELF_BILLING talent view:
    - Sees INV reference (client invoice raised in agency name)
    - Sees SBI reference (self-billing invoice raised on their behalf)
    - Sees COM reference (commission charged)
    - Sees net payout amount

  ON_BEHALF talent view:
    - Sees OBI reference (on-behalf invoice raised to client)
    - Sees COM reference (commission charged)
    - Sees net payout amount
    - NEVER sees the CN — credit note is an internal accounting document
    - NEVER sees another talent's invoices or payouts

NEVER:
- Calculate commission or net payouts on the client side
- Allow invoice amounts to be edited after they have been pushed to Xero
- Mark a milestone as payout-eligible until the corresponding INV or OBI
  is confirmed PAID in Xero (via webhook)
- Change InvoiceTriplet.issuedAt once approvalStatus='APPROVED' — enforced by DB trigger
- Push ON_BEHALF OBI to Xero without the matching settlement CN in the same approval batch
- Show a CN to the talent in the Talent Portal under any circumstances
- Populate both invNumber/sbiNumber AND obiNumber/cnNumber on the same
  InvoiceTriplet — they are mutually exclusive by invoicingModel


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 5. XERO INTEGRATION
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

Source of truth rule:
  Xero = source of truth for PAYMENT STATUS
  Therum = source of truth for INVOICE CREATION

ALWAYS:
- Disable Next.js body parser on the Xero webhook route:
    export const config = { api: { bodyParser: false } }
- Validate Xero webhook HMAC signature before processing any payload
  Use the raw request body (req.text()) for HMAC — never the parsed JSON
- Respond 200 to Xero within 5 seconds — offload heavy work to async
- Handle the intent-to-receive validation (empty events array) gracefully
- When pushing invoices to Xero, store the returned Xero invoice ID
  on the Therum record immediately for future webhook matching

Xero webhook HMAC pattern:
  const hmac = crypto
    .createHmac('sha256', process.env.XERO_WEBHOOK_KEY!)
    .update(rawBody)
    .digest('base64')
  if (hmac !== req.headers.get('x-xero-signature')) return 401

NEVER:
- Process a Xero webhook payload that fails HMAC validation
- Update invoice payment status in Supabase from client-side code
- Assume a Xero API call succeeded without checking the response status


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 6. STRIPE CONNECT
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

Therum uses Stripe Connect (Express accounts) for talent payouts.
Note: In Alpha/Beta, payouts are manual (PDF remittance statements).
Stripe Connect is wired but payouts are not yet automated.

ALWAYS:
- Validate Stripe webhook signatures using stripe.webhooks.constructEvent()
  with the raw request body
- Store stripeAccountId on both Agency and Talent records
- Include transfer_group metadata on every transfer linking to:
  dealId, milestoneId, SBI reference, payout run ID
- Check agency Stripe balance before initiating any payout run
  Gate the run if balance is insufficient

NEVER:
- Initiate a payout transfer before the corresponding INV is PAID in Xero
- Use stripe.payouts — use stripe.transfers for Connect payouts
- Store or log full card numbers or bank account numbers anywhere


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 7. VAT THRESHOLD MONITORING
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

UK VAT registration threshold is £90,000 on a rolling 12-month basis.
HMRC tests on date of supply (invoiceDate / issuedAt), not payment date.

Three alert tiers per talent:
  APPROACHING  £75,000  — warning banner in both portals
  IMMINENT     £85,000  — strong warning + email to finance contact
  BREACHED     £90,000  — critical alert

ALWAYS:
- Calculate rolling 12-month SBI gross using invoiceDate as the date basis
- Suppress VAT alerts for talent where talent.vatRegistered = true
- Include pipeline (contracted but not yet invoiced) in breach projections
- Recalculate on every new SBI creation or update

NEVER:
- Use payment date for VAT threshold calculations
- Show VAT alerts for VAT-registered talent


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 8. PORTAL ACCESS CONTROL
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

Three portal roles with completely different data access:

AGENCY role:
  - Full access to their own agency's deals, talent, clients
  - Cannot access Finance Portal features (invoice approval, payout runs)
  - Cannot see other agencies' data

FINANCE role:
  - Invoice approval queue, payout runs, Xero sync, VAT dashboard
  - Read-only access to deals and milestones (cannot create/edit deals)
  - Cannot access other agencies' data

TALENT role:
  - Can only see their OWN deals, milestones, payouts, remittances
  - SELF_BILLING: sees INV and SBI references
  - ON_BEHALF: sees OBI tab only — CN is NOT visible to talent
  - Cannot see commission amounts of other talent
  - Cannot see other talent's data within the same agency

ALWAYS:
- Check role server-side in every API route — never trust client-supplied role
- Use middleware to enforce portal access at the route level
- Return 403 (not 404) when a user accesses a resource outside their role


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 9. DATABASE & MIGRATIONS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

ALWAYS:
- Write every schema change as a Supabase migration file in /supabase/migrations
- Name migrations with timestamp prefix: 20260419_add_invoice_triplet.sql
- Include the RLS policy in the same migration as the table creation
- Add indexes on: agency_id, talent_id, deal_id, xero_invoice_id,
  stripe_transfer_id on any table that will be queried by these fields
- Use UUIDs for all primary keys

NEVER:
- Make schema changes directly in Supabase dashboard without a migration file
- Delete or modify existing migration files — always add new ones
- Store monetary amounts as floats — use integer (pence/cents) or
  numeric(10,2) for all financial figures


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 10. API ROUTE PATTERNS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

ALWAYS:
- Validate and sanitise all incoming request bodies with Zod before
  touching the database
- Return consistent error shapes:
    { error: string, code: string, details?: any }
- Log errors with enough context to debug: agency_id, user_id,
  relevant record IDs, timestamp
- Use HTTP status codes correctly:
    200 OK, 201 Created, 400 Bad Request, 401 Unauthorised,
    403 Forbidden, 404 Not Found, 409 Conflict, 500 Server Error
- Wrap database operations that must succeed together in a Supabase
  transaction or RPC function — especially INV/SBI/COM creation

NEVER:
- Return stack traces or internal error messages to the client
- Perform multiple dependent database writes outside a transaction
  (e.g. creating INV without SBI and COM is an invalid state)
- Skip input validation because "the frontend already validated it"


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 11. CODE QUALITY
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

ALWAYS:
- Use TypeScript strictly — no `any` types on financial data structures
- Define explicit types for InvoiceTriplet, Milestone, Deal, Payout
- Write a brief comment above any financial calculation explaining
  what it represents in plain English
- Keep API route handlers thin — extract business logic into
  /lib/services/ functions that can be tested independently
- Name functions and variables to reflect the domain:
  Good: calculateNetPayout(), generateInvoiceTriplet(), markMilestonePaid()
  Bad: processData(), handleItem(), doThing()

NEVER:
- Inline complex financial logic in React components
- Use console.log in production code — use a proper logger
- Suppress TypeScript errors with @ts-ignore on financial logic


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 12. THINGS THAT MUST NEVER HAPPEN IN THERUM
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

The following would constitute serious product failures:

1. Agency A can see Agency B's deals, invoices, or talent data
2. A talent payout is triggered before the client invoice is marked PAID
3. An INV is created without its corresponding SBI and COM
4. A payout amount is calculated client-side
5. The Xero webhook processes a payload with an invalid HMAC signature
6. InvoiceTriplet.issuedAt is modified after approvalStatus='APPROVED'
7. A talent in the ON_BEHALF model sees a credit note in their portal
8. VAT threshold calculations use payment date instead of invoiceDate
9. The Supabase service role key is exposed to the browser
10. A payout run proceeds when the Stripe balance is insufficient
11. ON_BEHALF: OBI is pushed to Xero without the matching settlement CN and COM
    in the same Finance approval batch (breaks P&L netting)

If any code change risks causing one of these outcomes, STOP and
flag it explicitly before proceeding.
